    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-12-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-12-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="123"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d123">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_EISENHOWERGADD1">Eisenhower</persName> Library, <persName
                        corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">Dulles</persName> papers, “Telephone
                    Conversations”</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Telephone Conversation</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d123fn1">The identity of the drafting officer is not
                        indicated on the source text.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1953-12-01">December 1,
                            1953</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Secretary telephoned Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BOWIERR1">Bowie</persName> and
                    said he thought the Candor Speech was likely to see the light of day, at least
                    to the point of bringing it up as a proposal at Bermuda.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d123fn2">Regarding the Bermuda Conference, Dec. 4–8, see the
                        editorial note, <ref target="#pg_1285">p. 1285</ref>.</note> The President
                    went over it last night and marked it up. He did quite a bit in the direction of
                    cutting out some of the stuff that could be offensive to the Soviet Union,
                    although he didn’t believe he did a great deal of toning down in other respects.
                        <persName corresp="#p_BOWIERR1">Bowie</persName> wanted to know how we would
                    get our oar in and the Secretary said he would call the White House and ask for
                    a copy of the draft as soon as it is retyped.</p>
                <p>[Here follows discussion of other subjects.]</p>
            </div>
        </body>
